After shipping multiple Flutter apps — from attendance trackers to AI-powered learning platforms — I've used both Bloc and Provider extensively. Here's what I've learned about when to use each.

## The Quick Answer

- **Provider**: Great for simple to moderate state. Less boilerplate, faster to set up.
- **Bloc**: Better for complex state flows. More structure, easier to test and debug.

## Provider in Practice

Provider shines when your state logic is straightforward:

```dart
class AttendanceProvider extends ChangeNotifier {
  bool _isCheckedIn = false;

  bool get isCheckedIn => _isCheckedIn;

  Future<void> checkIn(String location) async {
    final result = await _repository.checkIn(location);
    _isCheckedIn = result.success;
    notifyListeners();
  }
}
```

Use it in your widget:

```dart
Consumer<AttendanceProvider>(
  builder: (context, provider, child) {
    return ElevatedButton(
      onPressed: provider.isCheckedIn ? null : () => provider.checkIn(location),
      child: Text(provider.isCheckedIn ? 'Checked In' : 'Check In'),
    );
  },
)
```

### When Provider Works Best

- Settings and preferences
- Simple CRUD operations
- Small to medium apps
- Rapid prototyping

## Bloc in Practice

Bloc enforces a clear separation between events, states, and business logic:

```dart
// Events
sealed class QuizEvent {}
class AnswerSubmitted extends QuizEvent {
  final int questionIndex;
  final String answer;
  AnswerSubmitted(this.questionIndex, this.answer);
}

// States
sealed class QuizState {}
class QuizInProgress extends QuizState {
  final int currentQuestion;
  final int totalQuestions;
  QuizInProgress(this.currentQuestion, this.totalQuestions);
}
class QuizCompleted extends QuizState {
  final int score;
  QuizCompleted(this.score);
}

// Bloc
class QuizBloc extends Bloc<QuizEvent, QuizState> {
  QuizBloc() : super(QuizInProgress(0, 10)) {
    on<AnswerSubmitted>(_onAnswerSubmitted);
  }

  void _onAnswerSubmitted(AnswerSubmitted event, Emitter<QuizState> emit) {
    // Process answer, advance or complete
  }
}
```

### When Bloc Works Best

- Complex state transitions (quiz flows, multi-step forms)
- Apps requiring thorough testing
- Large teams needing consistent patterns
- Features with many interrelated states

## My Rule of Thumb

| Factor | Provider | Bloc |
|--------|----------|------|
| Boilerplate | Low | High |
| Testability | Good | Excellent |
| Learning curve | Easy | Moderate |
| Complex flows | Adequate | Excellent |
| Team scalability | Good | Excellent |

## Real-World Decision

For the **Mobile Attendance App**, I chose Provider — simple check-in/check-out state, minimal complexity.

For the **Quiz Assessment App**, I chose Bloc — multi-step quiz flow with scoring, timers, and result tracking needed clear state transitions.

## Conclusion

Don't pick a state management solution based on popularity. Pick based on your app's actual complexity. Start with Provider, graduate to Bloc when the state logic outgrows `ChangeNotifier`.
